				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/columnists/white-collar-watch/">White Collar Watch</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">The Year in White-Collar Crime</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Peter J. Henning			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-12-29T18:06:16+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 29, 2014 1:06 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 29, 2014 1:06 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/29/the-year-in-white-collar-crime/" data-title="The Year in White-Collar Crime" data-description="The new year will bring cases from the subprime mortgage crisis, a Justice Department decision on an appeal of an insider trading ruling and, perhaps, new accounting frauds, Peter J. Henning writes in the White Collar Watch column. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w225 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/30/business/dbpix-mozilo/dbpix-mozilo-blog225.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/30/business/dbpix-mozilo/dbpix-mozilo-blog225.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/30/business/dbpix-mozilo/dbpix-mozilo-blog225.jpg" id="100000003421953" width="225" height="142" alt="Angelo R. Mozilo, former chief executive of Countrywide Financial, may be back in the news again if a new round of civil fraud charges is filed."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="142"><meta itemprop="width" content="225"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Angelo R. Mozilo, former chief executive of Countrywide Financial, may be back in the news again if a new round of civil fraud charges is filed.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Tim Sloan/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">White-collar crime cases can take years to develop, so todayâs headlines often reflect what happened well in the past. And as we approach the end of 2014, there is a sense, to steal a line from <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/yogi_berra/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Yogi Berra.">Yogi Berra</a>, that itâs like dÃ©jÃ  vu all over again.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We will, of course, see continued fallout from the practices that helped fuel the financial crisis. This past year, the Justice Department reached multibillion-dollar settlements with <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BAC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Bank of America Corporation">Bank of America</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=JPM&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about JPMorgan Chase &#038; Company">JPMorgan Chase</a> for selling shoddy mortgage-backed securities before the financial crisis hit in 2008. Most of the loans packaged for investors were made by companies acquired by the banks as the real estate market spiraled downward in 2008, so they paid for the sins of others.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The settlements with big banks hardly close out cases from the financial crisis as names from the past keep popping to the surface. DealBook reported that the Justice Department was <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/justice-department-is-weighing-civil-suit-against-angelo-mozilo/">considering a civil fraud case</a> against <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/angelo_r_mozilo/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Angelo R. Mozilo.">Angelo R. Mozilo</a>, former chief executive of <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/countrywide_financial_corporation/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Countrywide Financial Corporation.">Countrywide Financial</a>, which was at the center of the subprime mortgage market. Prosecutors in Los Angeles closed a criminal investigation a few months after Mr. Mozilo reached a settlement with the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/s/securities_and_exchange_commission/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the U.S. Securities And Exchange Commission.">Securities and Exchange Commission</a> in 2010 over securities fraud charges. But he may be back in the news again if a new round of civil fraud charges is filed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <a href="//www.sec.gov/news/press/2011/2011-267.htm ">S.E.C. sued</a> the former chief executives of mortgage giants <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=FNMA&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Federal National Mortgage Association">Fannie Mae</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=FMCC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Freddie Mac">Freddie Mac</a>, along with other officers of the companies, for securities fraud in 2011 for not adequately disclosing the companiesâ exposure to the subprime mortgages that led to a government bailout.  Those cases are just winding up the discovery phase, so it is unlikely there will be a trial in 2015 as the two sides continue to fight over whether the case should proceed.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Add to those cases the Justice Departmentâs civil fraud lawsuit <a href="//www.justice.gov/opa/pr/department-justice-sues-standard-poor-s-fraud-rating-mortgage-backed-securities-years-leading">filed in 2013 against Standard &#038; Poor&#8217;s</a> for giving high ratings to mortgage-backed securities that collapsed during the financial crisis.  The two sides are still wrangling over what evidence should be produced in the case. So barring a settlement, the trial is unlikely to start until 2016, at the earliest.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The advent of 2015 is a chance to look at some of the trends in the world of white-collar crime that will play out over the next year. Here are a few thoughts:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Insider Trading</strong> The comedian Steven Wright has said, âIf everything seems to be going well, you have obviously overlooked something.â  The Justice Department learned that lesson the hard way in December when the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit in Manhattan threw out the insider trading convictions of two former hedge fund managers.  Along the way, the appeals court criticized the âdoctrinal noveltyâ of the governmentâs prosecution of recipients of information who were far removed from the sources inside companies providing advanced notice about corporate earnings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There is risk in every case that a jury may reject the charges, as the United States attorneyâs office in Manhattan saw when it <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/08/jury-clears-rengan-rajaratnam-in-insider-trading-case/">suffered its first loss</a> in an insider trading prosecution in July after a long string of victories since the arrest of <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/r/raj_rajaratnam/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Raj Rajaratnam.">Raj Rajaratnam</a> in 2009. But the appeals court decision has the potential for a much greater impact because the opinion adopted a heightened view of what is required to convict a recipient for trading on confidential information.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In future cases, the government will have to show that the tipper received something close to a tangible benefit for providing the information, and that so-called remote recipients who are a step removed from the source knew about that benefit. That will put a greater burden on the Justice Department and S.E.C. to uncover evidence establishing a relationship built on more than just pure friendship when information is passed along.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Justice Department will have to decide in January 2015 whether it will seek further review of the decision from all the active judges on the appeals court. If unsuccessful there, then a petition to the Supreme Court to review the case is possible. That department&#8217;s next move will tell us something about whether prosecutors and the S.E.C. believe they can live with the requirements for recipient liability adopted by the Federal Appeals Court for the Second Circuit.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The reversal of the convictions does not mean the government will back off from pursuing insider trading cases. Two days before Christmas, the S.E.C. filed <a href="//www.sec.gov/litigation/complaints/2014/comp-pr2014-291.pdf">civil charges against two Chilean businessmen</a> for trading on information about the acquisition of CFR Pharmaceuticals by <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=ABT&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Abbott Laboratories">Abbott Laboratories</a> that resulted in the two men making profit of about $10.6 million. One defendant was a director of CFR Pharmaceuticals, so the appeals court decision has no direct effect on this more traditional form of insider trading.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The Home-Court Advantage</strong> There is an old adage among lawyers that if the facts are against you, argue the law. If both the facts and the law are against you, then complain about where the case was filed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">An issue that is becoming increasingly contentious is a push by the S.E.C. to pursue more cases, including those involving insider trading charges, before in-house administrative law judges rather than in federal district court. Defense lawyers have decried the move because of the perception that the S.E.C. has something of a home-court advantage in an administrative proceeding. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A civil suit filed in federal district court gives each side the right to full discovery of the opponentâs information, a process that can stretch a case out for years. An administrative proceeding has a much shorter time frame as <a href="https://www.sec.gov/about/rulesprac2006.pdf">S.E.C. rules</a> allow only limited discovery and require an initial decision in less than a year in most cases. Importantly, there is no right to a jury to decide whether there was a violation, and the first appeal of a decision is to the S.E.C. commissioners who authorized the case in the first place. The Dodd-Frank Act expanded the use of administrative proceedings by authorizing the S.E.C. to pursue cases in this forum to obtain civil penalties for a violation, a remedy once reserved to federal judges.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Andrew Ceresney, the director of the S.E.C.âs enforcement division, defended the increased use of administrative proceedings <a href="//www.sec.gov/News/Speech/Detail/Speech/1370543515297#.VKAOEV4AAA">in a speech in November</a>. Rejecting concerns about the lack of a jury trial and limited discovery, he said, âOur use of the administrative forum is eminently proper, appropriate, and fair to respondents.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The S.E.C. is likely to have the upper hand on this issue because courts have generally upheld the use of administrative judges to decide cases. But that will not stop the white-collar defense bar from taking issue with the use of this forum by asking federal judges to overrule the S.E.C. on the grounds that the administrative proceeding deprives defendants of valuable rights. If a judge decides to block the use of administrative proceedings, then the issue will move to an appeals court and, perhaps, even the Supreme Court, to decide where securities fraud cases should be heard.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>The Role of Congress</strong> With the next Congress firmly in Republican control, we are almost sure to see legislative gridlock continue between Capitol Hill and the White House. In the search for common ground, however, two areas seem ripe for bipartisan legislation: jobs and fraud.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the employment front, there has been considerable frustration expressed in Congress over the S.E.C.âs failure to adopt rules to carry out the Jump Start Our Business Start-Ups Act, more commonly known as the JOBS Act. The law authorizes small businesses to appeal directly to the public to invest in a company, especially through crowdfunding portals. The S.E.C. was supposed to adopt rules by late 2012 to put the law into effect, but there has been little movement as proposed rules have languished.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/18/s-e-c-s-delay-on-crowdfunding-may-just-save-it-2/">Deal Professor pointed out</a>, some states are stepping forward with their own rules to allow crowdfunding. Congress certainly does not like being usurped by states or blocked by the S.E.C., so we can expect to see some form of JOBS Act II in 2015 to push the financing process forward.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fighting fraud is something every elected official can rally around, and the tool of choice these days seems to be encouraging more whistle-blowing of corporate wrongdoing by increasing the potential rewards. The Attorney General, <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/h/eric_h_holder_jr/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Eric H. Jr. Holder.">Eric H. Holder Jr.</a> is on board, calling <a href="//www.justice.gov/opa/speech/attorney-general-holder-remarks-financial-fraud-prosecutions-nyu-school-law">in a speech in September</a> for increased compensation for reporting fraud.  Senator <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/g/charles_e_grassley/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Charles E. Grassley.">Charles E. Grassley</a>, who is expected to be the chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee in 2015, has long been a proponent of whistle-blowing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whistle-blowers appear to have ascended to the level of mom and apple pie as an indisputable good.  So we can expect to see Congress expand programs to reward those who report violations, whether the victim is the government or a company.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Accounting Fraud</strong> <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/warren_e_buffett/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Warren E. Buffett.">Warren E. Buffett</a> once pointed out, âOnly when the tide goes out do you discover who&#8217;s been swimming naked.â The economic tide has certainly been rising, with the unemployment rate falling and the stock market regularly notching record highs. So it is almost like 1999 all over again. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How long ago it seems that accounting fraud felled companies like <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/enron/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Enron.">Enron</a> and WorldCom as the economy declined after the Internet bubble burst. Will that kind of misconduct come back?  As the economy gains strength, the pressure to report ever-increasing revenue and profit means that some corporate managers will be tempted cross the line in the belief that any little tweaks to financial reports can be made up as business gets better in the next year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Accounting problems are never far away, however. American Realty Capitalâs chief executive and two other officers stepped down recently because of issues with how the company reported revenue.  Reuters reported that the <a href="//www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/15/us-amer-rl-cap-prop-schorsch-idUSKBN0JT2AL20141215">F.B.I. is investigating the company</a>, which is never a good sign.<br />
Issues in a companyâs books usually donât come to light until months or years later, when the economy exposes who was cutting corners to earn those few extra pennies of profit. If the economy teeters in 2015, donât be surprised to learn that a few executives were swimming naked. </p>
<footer class="story-footer">
